Class ValueIteratorPopulatedTests

java.lang.Object
myTest.ValueIteratorPopulatedTests
public class ValueIteratorPopulatedTests extends Object
Test class for verifying the behavior of ValueIterator when the underlying map is populated. This class contains tests to ensure that the ValueIterator behaves correctly when iterating over a map with values.
See Also:
  • MapAdapter
  • MapAdapter.ValueIterator
  • MapAdapter.ValueCollection
Design
This test class is designed to ensure that the ValueIterator behaves correctly when the underlying map is populated. It verifies that the iterator can traverse all values, remove values as expected, and handle invalid operations gracefully. The test setup creates a map with 100 entries where values repeat every 50 keys to test behavior with duplicate values.
Libraries
JUnit 4.13, Hamcrest 1.3

  • Method Details

    • setUp

      public void setUp()
      Setup method to initialize the map and iterator before each test. This method is called before each test to ensure a fresh state.
      Design
      This setup method creates a MapAdapter with 100 entries where values repeat every 50 keys, ensuring we have duplicate values to test the ValueIterator behavior with repeated elements.
      Description
      Creates a map with 100 key-value pairs where keys are "key0" to "key99" and values are "value0" to "value49" (repeating). Then obtains the ValueCollection and its iterator for testing.
      Preconditions
      None - this is a setup method.
      Postconditions
      The map, values collection, and iterator are properly initialized and ready for testing.
      Expected Results
      The map should contain 100 entries with repeating values, and the iterator should be ready to traverse all values.

    • tearDown

      public void tearDown()
      Teardown method to clean up resources after each test.
      Design
      This teardown method sets all test instance variables to null to ensure proper cleanup and garbage collection.
      Description
      Sets the map, values collection, and iterator references to null after each test execution.
      Preconditions
      The test method has completed execution.
      Postconditions
      All test instance variables are set to null.
      Expected Results
      Memory resources are properly released.

    • testStartToFinish

      public void testStartToFinish()
      Test to verify that the ValueIterator can traverse all values from start to finish.
      Design
      This test verifies that the ValueIterator correctly implements the iteration protocol by checking that hasNext() and next() work together to traverse exactly the expected number of values.
      Description
      The test uses a while loop with hasNext() to iterate through all values using next(), counting each iteration. It then verifies that the total count matches the expected number of values in the collection (100).
      Preconditions
      The map must be populated with 100 entries before this test runs.
      Postconditions
      The iterator should have traversed all values exactly once.
      Expected Results
      The test should pass if the iterator traverses exactly 100 values, confirming that hasNext() and next() work correctly for the entire collection.

    • testRemoveAll

      public void testRemoveAll()
      Test to verify that the ValueIterator can remove all values through iteration.
      Design
      This test verifies that the ValueIterator's remove() method works correctly when called after each next() operation, and that removing all values results in an empty map.
      Description
      The test iterates through all values using hasNext() and next(), calling remove() after each next() call. It verifies that each returned value is not null and that the map becomes empty after all removals.
      Preconditions
      The map must be populated with 100 entries before this test runs.
      Postconditions
      The map should be empty after all values are removed through the iterator.
      Expected Results
      The test should pass if all values can be removed through the iterator and the map becomes empty.

    • testRemoveWithNext

      public void testRemoveWithNext()
      Test to verify that the ValueIterator can remove a single value after calling next().
      Design
      This test verifies that the ValueIterator's remove() method works correctly when called after a single next() operation, properly reducing the map size by the appropriate amount.
      Description
      The test calls hasNext() to verify an element exists, then calls next() to get a value, verifies the value is not null, calls remove() to remove the value, and checks that the map size is reduced by the expected amount (considering duplicate values).
      Preconditions
      The map must be populated with 100 entries before this test runs, and the iterator must have at least one element.
      Postconditions
      The map should have 99 entries after removing one value through the iterator.
      Expected Results
      The test should pass if a single value can be removed through the iterator and the map size is reduced to 99.

    • testRemoveWithoutNext

      public void testRemoveWithoutNext()
      Test to verify that the ValueIterator throws IllegalStateException when remove() is called without a preceding call to next().
      Design
      This test verifies that the ValueIterator properly enforces the contract that remove() can only be called after next() has been called, throwing IllegalStateException otherwise.
      Description
      The test attempts to call remove() immediately on a fresh iterator without calling next() first. This should result in an IllegalStateException being thrown.
      Preconditions
      The map must be populated and the iterator must be freshly created (no calls to next() yet).
      Postconditions
      The iterator and map should remain unchanged after the exception is thrown.
      Expected Results
      The test should pass if remove() throws an IllegalStateException when called without a preceding next() call.
